Turn around and keep walking.", 'Why isnâ€™t anyone talking about how he switched from a goatee to a mustache at 19:00 lol', 'damn i love this series...', 'the funk is a homage to project binky?', 'Amazing editing and I like your humor', 'Nik Blackhurst would be proud.', 'I guess no one noticed the difference 19:00  19:15 ğŸ˜‚', 'The reason you use "coolant" in radiators is the same reason you had such a mare with the thermostat housing bolts and the engine side panel bolts, the culprit is called galvanic corrosion, where steel has a different electrolitic signature to aluminium,   and this electrical difference causes any  aluminium in contact with steel to self destruct in its quest to oxidise back to oblivion and under constant heating and cooling cycles virtually welds the two together to the point you will destroy the aluminium well before the bond breaks, coolant contains added lubricants and anti oxidisers as well as ordinary antifreeze to prevent steel to alloy corrosion,  if working on old japanese kit again in the future ALWAYS make sure to re install every bolt and screw that goes into aluminium with a good quality anti seize compound, - you will be SO glad you did 12 months down the line if you ever have to remove them again. ["Thank you, everyone. Thank you for following along with me and also for being patient.

Sorry about all the noise!", 'Just a note. Never apply antisieze to the hub / rotor mating surface. Could cause the rotor to not sit true', 'This is amazing! I love this channel!', 'My dude has a whole mr2 a sonata and a Cruze in his driveway ğŸ˜‚', 'I thought the composite caliper pistons were cool, then i had an immediate vietnam flashback the second you said the word "phenolic"

If you don't know, phenolics are a type of resin/plastic. They can be used in a number of things. I used to work at a cabinetry/specialties shop, and some of our biggest selling specialties were bathroom stalls and counter tops, and every now and then we'd get an order for those products made out of phenolic. And boy let me tell you, that stuff is *dense*. Like, one 4x4 foot counter top, 1.5 inches thick would weigh upwards of 100lb. Gotta love carrying that shit up the stairs to the third floor of a building under constructionğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚', 'For fucks sakes mate, heat up the rotor in an oven, say 70 celsius or so, and blast the bearing race with lighter refill canister, butane and such are quite potent cooling agents when in absence of liquid nitrogen... That would have allowed you to drop that bearing race in the bearing seat, all the way in, absolutely no force required, and no chance of messing up the bearing or the bearing seat... It would result in a 100 degrees difference between the parts, which would likely be enough to induce a clearance, as the bearings are rarely a strong interference fit, most often they are light or rarely medium interference fit... The same works for taking them out... Heat up the whole part, blast the inner race with lighter gas, and it will likely fall out on its own if you are doing that upside down... The differential temperatures will cause a gap between the parts, and often, there is no need for more than a 100 degrees difference for the parts to separate on their own, and to prevent the heated part from cooling, or the desired cold part from soaking up the heat and thus remaining the same diameter... Save your effort, save the parts from damage, and avoid the potential for either injury or smashing something that you shouldnt with a hammer... A press is just as bad as the hammer, but it has a few benefits, yet if the parts can be differentially heated/cooled, its the best approach, and the safest one by a whole ballpark of a margin... I am a certified automechatronics tech, and a machinist/millwright, so i am quite familiar with bearings and the whole shebang of dealing with shit that is supposed to be somewhere or to be extracted from somewhere where it wants to remain... A car bearing aint no precision spindle bearing, but its a ``precision`` component nonetheless and should be treated with gentleness and every other method before resorting to force of any kind...

Also, keep in mind that that wheel nut should be moderately tight... The bearings may be tapered and thus become ever harder to turn, to the point where you either brinell the bearings or seize them and thus damage them... The similarity of this spindle and a high precision machine spindle still remains... That spindle stub is elastic, and as you tighten the nut, the spindle elongates elastically somewhat, that can be measured with an indicator... That is one thing to take into consideration... Another is the loads, be it side loads, lateral loads or whatever sort of insane vector of load forces a car produces while driving... Those forces are attempting to rip your wheel off constantly, the spindle`s structural integrity prevents that shit from happening, but as with the nut, those forces elongate the spindle a bit and let it contract as the load vector shifts... The bearings should actually be preloaded somewhat, akin to machine spindle, as to prevent the bearings from ever developing a clearance and a gap of any sort between the races and the rolling elements... That is what obliterates the bearings... A properly preloaded bearing will not under any normal circumstance develop a momentary loss of full contact between the races and the rolling elements, thus greatly increasing its lifetime and performance... I cant really tell you what force to use... That should either be in the manual of the vehicle, or you can calculate it relatively simply... Look up tapered bearing preload and such... You can look up machinist related content in that topic and apply the formula and explanation for the precision spindles for this... A bearing should be able to turn by hand when the wheel hub is tightly on, but there should be some resistance to turning, it should not freewheel for a minute, it should spin one turn at the most if all is well set up... A lack of proper preload can obliterate the bearings with ease, either through increased wear, brinelling of the races, chipping of the elements surfaces and so on... 

I know that im 4 years too late for this party, but i just found the channel yesterday... Sorry if the comment may appear hostile, as its not meant to be, its a heartfelt gentle suggestion, made for the sakes of precision parts that can serve you well or get fucked in a rush and add up quickly in cost and frustration if you keep on installing them improperly... Also, dont lubricate anything with brake fluid... Use atf or whatever else, but not the bloody brake fluid... That shit will turn acidic in a hurry when exposed to air, and well, no need to explain why acidic lubricant is bad... Use forklift grease in a spray can, use atf, use gearbox oil, bearing grease, earwax, whatever just not the brake fluid... That shit should never see anything other than the dark insides of either its storage pack or the inside of the brake system... Its an amazing compound, but its literally devils tears in any situation other than its packaging or the brake sys... 

All the best, and for the love of God, dont spend 1k$ on fucking wood... Buy some good bearings, or whatever the fuck else, just not ``engineered wood``... And in the worst case scenario, various combinations of wind, water, heat/cold, etc. can actually cause the ceramic to not adhere properly to the surface, requiring another buff  and polish step to remove the remaining ceramic and then a complete reapplication of the ceramic.

The advantage of getting clear coat and hardener separated is that it can stay at the shelf for longer time. The guys who made the paint for the car can do the clear coat with the hardener already mixed up which might be cheaper but it will also mean that it will expire in like two weeks.

Another point about electric polisher: if you don't have the experience and you are not planning with getting a wrap or stickers at it, you may easy create a holo effect just by pressing it too tough or keeping it for too long in one spot, which will look bad in the sun, so better stick to manual job at the begging.

['A common question in the comments is how can we have a junkyard engine and still be below the $500 limit and here is the answer: 
The goal of the 24hrs of Lemons is to try to level the playing field by having a bunch of junk cars race. This is the most affordable wheel to wheel racing in the world. Since our engine blew at our first  race and we are putting in an equally junky 140k mile junkyard M54 engine which is what came stock with our car, the replacement engine does not count towards the budget. The new seals we installed to stop the oil leaks ($60) and the chain tensioner we installed ($6) does count and the headers ($100) definitely count but we were at $340 after selling everything we could from the carâ€¦ So now we are at our $500 budget. I need to see if I can sell the cats because those are $400 but something tells me that we canâ€™t haha. 
With that said, safety stuff does not count towards the $500 budget. Otherwise itâ€™s impossible to race because the fire suppression system alone cost more than $500 and the cage cost $3800. Parts to make the car faster or perform better do count, but not stuff to save the drivers life. 
Now the â€œbackup engineâ€ is a good opportunity for a collab with another automotive YouTuber who wanted to get involved and is trying to grow his channel. We arenâ€™t using the backup engine unless ours blows up again which I canâ€™t imagine will happen (knock on wood). So that engine wonâ€™t count towards the budget because itâ€™s not in the car at the start of the race. If we end up having to swap it in at the track, it still wonâ€™t count because the time it takes to swap it in will make it so we are not competitive anymore. The next race we would have to remove it and put in another junk engine or take penalty laps. 
Lmk if you have any more questions about the $500 budget. Again, the main goal is to prevent people dumping money into a car and have an unfair advantage because they have a bunch of money.', 'I just searched up â€œproject carâ€ and started watching from when you first got this car, now itâ€™s 6 AM and I wanna build an endurance race car ğŸï¸ â¤', 'What oil anyalysis company did you use and have you done a YouTube on how to go about doing that?', 'Based on the combustion chamber, your mixture was right on!', 'Great data and analysis Chris!', 'Was that head cracked too? ["You should always go to O'Reilly or AutoZone instead of advance. Advance has a lot of lazy people and it takes them forever to come out to your vehicle. O'Reilly tends to be the best. Napa is even a bit better if they have one in your area. Also, there are tests done on the expensive vs. Cheap batteries and the cheap ones actually out do the expensive ones in certain test. It's more or less just money down the drain. The warranty is nice if you will keep the vehicle and hold onto your receipt.", "If you can, get a voltage meter that you can see at all times while driving. You can find ones online that go in the cigarette lighter if you have a car old enough for that, and they also can have USB charging. You will be able to see what is going on with your electrical system during different times. You may be having under voltage at idle but fine at driving speeds, this would give you an issue if you're in stop and go traffic, the battery would never get charged back up. You may have good voltage at idle but overcharging at driving speeds, this could damage your battery and other electrical components with highway/interstate driving. You will also see what is going on after you've driven a while and the alternator has had a chance to heat up.

The alternator produces electricity based on the rpm of the engine, so if your engine is bogging down at idle, it will lower the amount of voltage and amperage the alternator produces. If your air conditioner is aging and long over due for service, it can bog down the drive belt by introducing mechanical resistance at idle, thus slowing down the alternator. You could also have have a misfire or other idling issue causing your rpm to drop below intended amounts after the engine has warmed up.


Alternators like being cold and dry. If it's a hot and humid day, your alternator is going to perform worse. They also will perform better at crank up and the true performance may not be detected for a while until it starts heating up. ["To the smart asses saying they just wouldn't be lazy and check their tire pressure with an analog gauge. If your that proactive about checking your pressure good for you. But what you arent proactive enough to do is check your wheel temp.  So when your temp is significantly higher on one wheel compared to the other three you'll know somethings wrong and have it checked out. Its how i was able to diagnose that my wheel bearing was bad even though it hadnt started to make a  clear sound yet. But it did save me from chewing up a $300+ tire too badly. I think it had just started to cup. But it could have been a bad caliper or a couple other things thats best to catch as early as possible. ['ğŸ‡µğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡µğŸ‡¬,mm,', "I just want to make a short comment and yes it definitely is similar to a fuse or relay however there's nothing in today's world that replaces a fusible link unfortunately. Have a 1990 Dodge van that has a lot of fusible links I would love to substitute them but it is very complicated because even though they protect in the same manner there's nothing that will allow a current to come through and not pop it the way a fusible link works. A fuse any current coming through that is too high will pop at immediately relay will turn it off and then turn it back on immediately.. fusible link allows up to 3 seconds of current to go through so if you have surges in the system (an old van like mine there are many) The fusible link allows for them whereas the fuses and relays don't. Many people replace them but there are issues with doing that I wish there was a direct replacement. It's fine when you have one fusible link but when you have 20 of them it's really a pain", 'you said "don\'t forget to put the heat shrink on the wires before soldering and crimping"...what do you mean, because how can you crimp and solder if the plastic heat shrink is already over the area being fused?', 'Use flux next time and it will look as good as your example did', "I need you in my lifetime you're the reason I work and fix whatever I can but I also know when to leave it to the pros. Very thorough and don't listen to anyone else's opinions on how soldering looks. If it is bonded together WHO CARES? I THINK YOU DID AN AMAZING JOB", "Your soldering result was ugly because your soldering iron didn't produce sufficient heat for that job & because you didn't use sufficient flux.  Good vid nevertheless--it shows the essential info, so thank you!", 'The FL is usually tinned copper high stranding wire with a Hypalon (high temp, will not catch fire) insulating jacket. An blown FL will have a rippled and distorted look to the jacket (insulation). Although, as seen in the video, the failure mode is more often corrosion than an internally shorted Alternator.\n\nI prefer to use round barrel step down butt splices (hydraulic crimp) with Red dual wall heat shrink when repairing FLs. I do not solder fusible links. One of the many reasons is, for a large wire gauge splice like in the video, is the amount of heat needed to solder the joint correctly can actually over temp the FL jacket which will make it look like it experienced and overload (over temp) condition, because this is how you identify an overloaded FL. So, to avoid this, it is best to use a barrel butt splice connection(s).', 'Why would that link make your speedometer move??', 'Hey Boss, what kind of crimp is that? And what other types of crimps are acceptable? Can I also just solder the wire well and use heat shrink tubing?', 'The close caption sometimes interferes with the video. Great video. ['Voy a explicar lo de las ruedas en lluvia que veo mucha gente comentandolo.

Con ruedas mas anchas es mas facil hacer aguaplaning, es decir cuando hay balsas de agua en la carretera el coche se desliza mas facil sobre ellas, como una tabla en la orilla de la playa. 

Pero en lluvia, con la carretera simplemente mojada, unas ruedas mas anchas deslizan menos lateralmente, frenan mejor y en resumen agarran mas.

Cuando es recomendable llevar finas es con nieve, con charcos, o cuando tu coche es muy ligero y no tiene nada de carga aerodinamica, como los utilitarios. En resumen cuando es mas util que "se hinque" en la superficie a que se agarre. 

Diferencias reales en un coche tipico (golf): 
- Con neumaticos de 195mm haces aguaplaning a 87,8kmh y con 225mm a 85kmh
- En mojado los anchos frenan antes y agarran bastante mas en curvas.

['Espero que os guste el coche, aclaro unos detalles en los que no me queria extender (+tocho)

No os quedeis con que los compresores son mejores que los turbos porque no tiene por que.
Lo digo porque estoy recibiendo mensajes de gente con coches turbo que quieren quitarlo y ponerle un compresor *(wtf)*

Si *es mejor en este caso* es porque no es un motor al que se le deba sacar mucha potencia si quieres cuidarlo, la transmision y los internals no aguantarian bien el par de un turbo, ni siquiera pasar de 350cv sin cambiar medio motor y la caja de cambios.

No es viable ni rentable ponerle algo asi a tu arosa o coches de ese tipo, lo mejor en casi todos los casos es directamente cambiar de coche a uno mejor. Si no lo hago en este es porque no hay muchos mas coches como este que no sean superdeportivos carisimos que no me puedo permitir (si, para mi este coche es un "quiero y no puedo" de un lexus lfa)

La gracia de este coche y uno de los motivos por los que me gusta es porque esta pensado para un tipo de uso y para transmitir unas *sensaciones, que directamente se perderian si le pongo un turbo.* Pero poniendo un compresor mantienes todo eso igual, aunque es dificil de explicar porque no es algo que se mida en cifras.

Cuando digo que bajar un coche, aumentarle el tamaÃ±o de las ruedas y hacerlo mas ancho no sirve para nada me refiero en la vida real en la calle, no en un circuito o en el gran turismo. 

Pero aun asi, incluso en circuito, un coche como este que apenas da 180cv reales de serie, con unas ruedas enormes lo unico que va a hacer es gastar mas gasolina, ser mas lento y mas torpe. 
Porque esas llantas aunque son la ostia de bonitas, pesan un huevo y son bastante mierder, mientras las de serie son super ligeras y top, al final es mucho mas util poner unos neumaticos buenos si quieres agarre. 

Y normalmente cuando compensa poner ruedas mas grandes es en coches con tanta potencia que no pueden transmitirla al suelo y salen quemando rueda durante 2 o 3 marchas (es lo que hice en el camaro porque son 435nm de par, el gt86 unos 200nm)

Y lo de los escapes que hacen ruido y tal pues bueno va en gustos, pero si no dejas dormir a la gente como seria mi caso pues te merecerias una pedrada y lo sabes jaja.
Si viviese lejos de la ciudad que es algo que me gustaria en un futuro pues entonces ni tan mal, aunque lo pondria con valvula y control remoto para cerrar el escape al llegar a zonas con gente como hizo ford con el nuevo mustang.

Casi siempre cuento estas cosas y luego al editar el video las acabo borrando, porque si llego a contar todo esto el video habria durado 20 minutos y seria un rollo.
Yo los hago para que sean entretenidos y pasarlo bien viendolos, asi que espero que los disfruteis y os sean utiles.
